    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-10-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-10-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="482" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d482">
                <head>No. 27.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Graland</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-10-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 13,
                                1887</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg to acknowledge your communication of
                            yesterday’s date, by which I am surprised to learn of the failure of the
                            United States marshal at Sitka to obey the instruction of the President
                            of January 26 last, for the immediate release of the British sealers <hi rend="italic">Onward, Carolena</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">Thornton</hi>. I have felt it to be my duty at once to communicate
                            this information to the British minister at this capital.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
